        "text": "1 Kings 9:1-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The general contents, and the order of the thoughts in the divine answer in the two texts, agree, but in the Chronicle individual thoughts are further expounded than in the book of Kings, and expressions are here and there made clear. The second clause of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is an instance of this, where \"and all the desire of Solomon, which he was pleased to do,\" is represented by \"and all that came into Solomon's heart, to make in the house of the Lord and in his own house, he prosperously effected.\" Everything else is explained in the Com. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9",
        "children": []
      },
